questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pulling hand from the flame&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reflex actions&lt;/strong&gt; are automatic and rapid responses to a stimulus that do not require conscious thought.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Pulling your hand away from a flame is a classic example of a reflex action, specifically a &lt;strong&gt;withdrawal reflex&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This action is controlled by the &lt;strong&gt;spinal cord&lt;/strong&gt;, not the brain, which allows for a much quicker response to potential danger.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The reflex arc is the neural pathway that mediates this action, involving sensory neurons, interneurons, and motor neurons.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Reflex Arc:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The reflex arc is the neural pathway that controls a reflex action.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It typically involves a sensory neuron, an interneuron, and a motor neuron.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The sensory neuron detects a stimulus and sends a signal to the interneuron in the spinal cord, which then activates the motor neuron to produce a response.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Types of Reflexes:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Monosynaptic reflexes&lt;/strong&gt;: Involve only one synapse between the sensory and motor neurons (e.g., knee-jerk reflex).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Polysynaptic reflexes&lt;/strong&gt;: Involve multiple synapses with one or more interneurons (e.g., withdrawal reflex).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Autonomic Reflexes:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These reflexes regulate the activity of smooth muscles, the heart, and glands.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include the regulation of blood pressure, digestion, and pupil size.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Somatic Reflexes:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These reflexes involve the skeletal muscles.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Examples include the stretch reflex and withdrawal reflex.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Both cranial and spinal nerves&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The peripheral nervous system (PNS) consists of all the nerves that lie outside the brain and spinal cord.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It includes 12 pairs of cranial nerves and 31 pairs of spinal nerves.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The cranial nerves originate from the brain and primarily serve the head and neck region.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The spinal nerves originate from the spinal cord and serve the rest of the body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The PNS is responsible for transmitting sensory and motor information to and from the central nervous system (CNS).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Central Nervous System (CNS)&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It consists of the brain and spinal cord.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The CNS is responsible for processing and interpreting sensory information and sending out instructions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Autonomic Nervous System (ANS)&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a part of the PNS that controls involuntary bodily functions.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The ANS is divided into the sympathetic and parasympathetic nervous systems.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Somatic Nervous System&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is another part of the PNS that controls voluntary movements.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The somatic nervous system transmits sensory and motor signals to and from the CNS.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neurons&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are the basic building blocks of the nervous system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Neurons transmit information through electrical and chemical signals.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

questions.statement:
&lt;p&gt;Which of the following is/are related to the practical applications of electricity in daily life?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(A) Electric oven.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(B) Electric laundry iron.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;(C) Solar water heater&lt;/p&gt;

questions.explanation:
&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Only (A) and (B)&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Electric oven &amp;mdash; Uses electricity directly to generate heat.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Electric laundry iron &amp;mdash; Also uses electricity directly for heating.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Solar water heater &amp;mdash; Primarily uses solar energy (sunlight) to heat water, not electricity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;So, only (A) and (B) are related to practical applications of electricity in daily life.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electricity in Domestic Use&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electricity powers a range of household appliances including refrigerators, washing machines, and air conditioners, enhancing modern living standards.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electric lights provide illumination, significantly extending the usable hours of the day.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Home entertainment systems, such as televisions and computers, rely on electricity, contributing to leisure and connectivity.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Renewable Energy Applications&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Solar panels convert sunlight into electricity, representing a clean and sustainable energy source.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Wind turbines harness wind energy to generate electricity, contributing to renewable energy production.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Energy Efficiency&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Energy-efficient appliances reduce electricity consumption and lower utility bills.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Smart home systems allow for automated control of electrical devices, enhancing energy management.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Electricity in Communication&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Electricity is critical for powering communication devices such as smartphones, routers, and servers.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The internet and telecommunication infrastructure rely heavily on a stable electrical supply.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;It will be doubled.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law states that the current (I) flowing through a resistor is directly proportional to the voltage (V) across it and inversely proportional to the resistance (R). The formula is I = V/R.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the resistance (R) is halved and the voltage (V) remains constant, the current (I) will increase.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Mathematically, if the initial resistance is R and it is halved to R/2, the new current will be I_new = V / (R/2) = 2V/R = 2I_initial.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Therefore, halving the resistance while keeping the voltage constant will result in the current being doubled.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Ohm&amp;#39;s Law:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Formulated by Georg Simon Ohm in 1827.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Defines the relationship between voltage, current, and resistance in an electrical circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Expressed as V = IR, where V is voltage, I is current, and R is resistance.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Resistance:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Measured in ohms (&amp;Omega;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Determines how much a material opposes the flow of electric current.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Factors affecting resistance include material, length, cross-sectional area, and temperature.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Current:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Measured in amperes (A).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Represents the flow of electric charge in a circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Can be direct (DC) or alternating (AC).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Voltage:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Measured in volts (V).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Represents the electrical potential difference between two points.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Provides the driving force that pushes the current through the circuit.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;an oxidising agent&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bleaching powder (Calcium hypochlorite) is a strong oxidising agent, which means it can donate oxygen to other substances and oxidize them.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is commonly used in chemical industries for bleaching paper pulp, textiles, and disinfecting drinking water due to its ability to kill bacteria and other pathogens.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Bleaching powder releases chlorine when exposed to air and moisture, which contributes to its oxidising properties.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is widely used in the textile industry to bleach cotton and linen and in the paper industry to bleach wood pulp.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Oxidising Agents&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Oxidising agents are substances that can accept electrons and bring about oxidation of other substances.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common oxidising agents include substances like hydrogen peroxide, potassium permanganate, and chlorine.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;They are used in various industrial processes including disinfection, bleaching, and water treatment.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calcium Hypochlorite&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Calcium hypochlorite, commonly known as bleaching powder, is a white solid, often used for water treatment and as a bleaching agent.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Its chemical formula is Ca(ClO)&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is more stable than sodium hypochlorite (liquid bleach) and has a longer shelf life.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Disinfection Process&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Disinfection involves the elimination of most or all pathogenic microorganisms, except bacterial spores, from inanimate objects.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Bleaching powder is used to disinfect drinking water and swimming pools by killing harmful microorganisms.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Safety Measures&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;When handling bleaching powder, it is important to use protective gear, such as gloves and masks, to avoid irritation and inhalation of fumes.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It should be stored in a dry, cool place away from organic materials and acids to prevent hazardous reactions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The SI unit of force is called the &lt;strong&gt;Newton&lt;/strong&gt;, symbolized as &amp;quot;N&amp;quot;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;One Newton is defined as the amount of force required to accelerate a &lt;strong&gt;1 kilogram mass by 1 meter per second squared&lt;/strong&gt; (1 N = 1 kg&amp;middot;m/s&amp;sup2;).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The Newton is named after Sir &lt;strong&gt;Isaac Newton&lt;/strong&gt; in recognition of his work in classical mechanics, particularly Newton&amp;#39;s Laws of Motion.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The unit was adopted in the International System of Units (SI) in &lt;strong&gt;1948&lt;/strong&gt; during the 9th General Conference on Weights and Measures (CGPM).&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Dyne&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A dyne is a unit of force in the centimeter-gram-second (CGS) system of units.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is equal to 10^-5 Newtons (1 dyne = 10^-5 N).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Newton&amp;#39;s Laws of Motion&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;There are three fundamental laws that describe the relationship between the motion of an object and the forces acting on it.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These laws form the foundation of classical mechanics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Force&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;In physics, force is an interaction that, when unopposed, will change the motion of an object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It can be described as a push or pull on an object resulting from the object&amp;#39;s interaction with another object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;SI Units&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The International System of Units (SI) is the modern form of the metric system.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is the most widely used system of measurement, established in 1960.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sugar and sponge&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sugar&lt;/strong&gt; is a crystalline solid that retains its shape and volume under standard conditions.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Sponge&lt;/strong&gt; is a porous solid material that can compress and return to its original shape, demonstrating solid-state characteristics.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Both sugar and sponge have a defined shape and volume, which are key characteristics of solids.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Unlike liquids or gases, the molecules in solids such as sugar and sponge are closely packed together, providing rigidity and stability.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;States of Matter:&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The three primary states of matter are solid, liquid, and gas.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Solids have a fixed shape and volume, liquids have a fixed volume but take the shape of their container, and gases neither have a fixed shape nor a fixed volume.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Properties of Solids:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Solids are characterized by their rigidity and resistance to changes in shape or volume.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The particles in a solid are tightly packed in a regular pattern, which gives solids their definite shape and volume.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Crystalline and Amorphous Solids:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Crystalline solids, like sugar, have an orderly structure with repeating patterns.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Amorphous solids, like sponges, do not have a long-range order and can be more flexible in shape.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Compressibility:&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Solids generally have low compressibility compared to liquids and gases.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Sponge is an exception due to its porous structure, allowing it to compress and expand.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;less than the density of the liquid&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;An object will float on a liquid if its density is &lt;strong&gt;less than the density of the liquid&lt;/strong&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This is due to the principle of &lt;strong&gt;buoyancy&lt;/strong&gt;, where the upward buoyant force exerted by the liquid balances the weight of the object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;If the density of the object is higher than the liquid, it will sink because the weight of the object is greater than the buoyant force.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Objects with density equal to the liquid&amp;#39;s density will remain suspended at any depth within the liquid.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Buoyancy&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Buoyancy is the force exerted by a fluid that opposes the weight of an immersed object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;The magnitude of the buoyant force is equal to the weight of the fluid displaced by the object.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Archimedes&amp;#39; Principle&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It states that the buoyant force on an object is equal to the weight of the fluid displaced by the object.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;This principle helps in determining whether an object will float or sink in a fluid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Density&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Density is defined as mass per unit volume and is usually expressed in kilograms per cubic meter (kg/m&amp;sup3;).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;It is a key factor in determining whether an object will float or sink in a fluid.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Specific Gravity&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Specific gravity is the ratio of the density of a substance to the density of a reference substance (typically water).&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;If the specific gravity of an object is less than 1, it will float in water.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Regeneration&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Regeneration is the process by which organisms replace or restore lost or amputated body parts.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Planaria are a type of flatworm capable of regenerating an entire organism from a small fragment of their body.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;This process involves the proliferation of stem cells called neoblasts, which differentiate into various cell types needed for regeneration.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Regeneration in Planaria is a highly studied phenomenon, providing insights into cellular differentiation and developmental biology.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Binary Fission&lt;/strong&gt;

	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A form of asexual reproduction where a single organism divides into two parts, each becoming a new organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Commonly observed in prokaryotic microorganisms like bacteria and archaea.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Fragmentation&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A form of asexual reproduction where an organism is split into fragments, each of which develops into a new organism.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Common in organisms like starfish, some annelid worms, and fungi.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Multiple Fission&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;A form of asexual reproduction where a single organism divides into multiple daughter cells simultaneously.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Seen in some protozoa, such as Plasmodium (the malaria parasite).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Neoblasts&lt;/strong&gt;
	&lt;ul&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;Pluripotent stem cells found in Planaria responsible for their regenerative abilities.&lt;/li&gt;
		&lt;li&gt;These cells can differentiate into various cell types required for tissue regeneration and repair.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;/ul&gt;
	&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The correct answer is &lt;u&gt;&lt;strong&gt;gypsum is heated at 373 K and it loses water molecules&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/u&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/key-point-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;u style=&quot;font-size: 21px; font-weight: bolder; font-family: var(--bs-body-font-family); text-align: var(--bs-body-text-align);&quot;&gt;Key Points&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;Plaster of Paris is chemically known as calcium sulfate hemihydrate.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;It is prepared by heating gypsum (calcium sulfate dihydrate) at about 373 K (100&amp;deg;C).&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;During this process, gypsum loses water molecules to form Plaster of Paris.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;The chemical equation for this process is:&lt;br /&gt;
	CaSO&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;middot;2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O (gypsum) &amp;rarr; CaSO&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;middot;0.5H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O (Plaster of Paris) + 1.5H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;display: flex;gap: 6px;align-items: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img height=&quot;26px&quot; src=&quot;//cdn.testbook.com/resources/lms_creative_elements/additional-information-image.png&quot; width=&quot;26px&quot; /&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;vertical-align: middle;font-size: 21px;&quot;&gt;&lt;u&gt;Additional Information&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Gypsum&lt;/strong&gt;: A mineral composed of calcium sulfate dihydrate, with the chemical formula CaSO&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;middot;2H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Calcium sulfate hemihydrate&lt;/strong&gt;: The chemical name for Plaster of Paris, with the formula CaSO&lt;sub&gt;4&lt;/sub&gt;&amp;middot;0.5H&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;O.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Uses of Plaster of Paris&lt;/strong&gt;: Commonly used for making sculptures, molds, and casts; also in construction for finishing walls and ceilings.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Setting reaction&lt;/strong&gt;: When mixed with water, Plaster of Paris rehydrates and sets into a hard solid, reforming into gypsum.&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Temperature control&lt;/strong&gt;: The heating temperature must be controlled carefully to ensure proper formation of Plaster of Paris without decomposing it to anhydrous calcium sulfate.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;
